 @ericsimmons4868  Go tell that to Tesla. The autopilots on planes are that way because of extensive certifications, so they mostly follow preset waypoints. The ones currently being used on commercial aviation don't have problem solving capabilities.

Having that said, the Cirrus jets and others can basically turn on and pre-check at the push of a button, and there's a new emergency landing system "Vision Jet: Safe Return Emergency Autoland" available for it.

These innovations are all coming, sooner than you'd like to believe.

 @geopearlst  Not accurate.  A lot of good and a lot of marginal employees have come and gone in my 20 years in this business.  The ones who stay (or longer) as long as I have do so because we are good at what we do.  We love what we because we believe in our mission.  

Now, those of us who didn't just get up and leave when presented with a s--- sandwich found other things to do within our Department.  Our #2 in the office leapfrogged his boss (Mr. There's The Door) and now is one of decision makers within the Department.  I took a different position that better suits me.  

To say that people stayed because they only care about a paycheck is overly simplistic.

 @crzy11000  Everything you described is one hat, that of "clerk" or "associate" or whatever you choose to call your employees, and you're absolutely justified in expecting them to do such.  

Now imagine you took the entry level part-timer you just hired and told them "once you're done with the garbage, I need you to run up to the office and take care of the accounting for the month".  That's what many "We wear lots of hats" folk try to pull.  

You aren't asking them to do work way beyond their pay grade for free by telling them to handle the trash.

 @Portsguy1234567  I always avoided the company outings and told people that I don't believe in "enforced happiness".
If I want to hang out with the folks from work that I like it's a lot easier to do so without having the ones that I dislike around.
Although...the best time that I ever had was when I went to a company picnic one day and my terrible boss thought that his daughter and I had hooked up. I acted totally innocent and she told him that who she dated was none of his business. It was fun thereafter watching him go slowly insane...over nothing.

@Nathan M  I'll be honest, I can't really relate.  I hire a fair number of entry level employees for a very large multi-national company, and the expectation for most hires is something like "anything they accomplish in the first 90 days is gravy" and no one is really expected to be any good at all until they've been in a role for 6 months (then it just depends on the person).

Earlier than that, someone might do good work, and you might believe they're going to be good at the job, but you're really just looking for traits and fit and not at numbers.

I guess it depends on the role, but if it's a job that requires a college degree or years of experience to be hired, then a lot is expected, which paradoxically means not a lot is expected right away.

